ry can also provide essential insights into the subject. Metaphors of Spain brings together leading historians to examine Spanish nationalism through its diverse and complementary cultural artifacts, from “formal” representations such as the flag to music, bullfighting, and other more diffuse examples. Together they describe not a Spanish national “essence,” but a nationalism that is constantly evolving and accommodates multiple interpretations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aNationalismzSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and culturezSpainxHistoryy20th century. 0aRegionalismzSpainxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aart.  aautocratic rule.  abullfighting.  achristianity.  acultural artifacts.  acultural history.  aengaging.  aeurope.  aeuropean history.  afrancisco franco.  ahistory.  aleading historians.  amodern spain.  amusic.  anationalism.  anobility.  apage turner.  apolitical character.  apolitical ideologies.  apolitical science.  apolitical.  apolitics.  aportugal.  arealistic.  aregional identities.  areligion.  areligious conflict.  arevolution.  aroyalty.  aseparatist tensions.  aspanish culture.  aspanish history.  aspanish nationalism.1 aDuarte, Àngel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlorencio, Rafael Núñez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerranz, Inmaculada Blasco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolguín, Sandie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJunco, José Álvarez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcilhacy, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoreno